[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Playing against e4:  The Alekhine"]
[Black "Exchange variation:  The dreaded Voronezh"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4
{ If you follow the 'most commonly played' moves in low level Alekhine's games, you find that you end up in the exchange variation.  It is appropriate to play c4 first, to cut out some strange lines with ...Qxd6. }
4... Nb6 5. exd6
{ But now, recapturing with both the e pawn and the c pawn have been popular.  The c pawn was the traditional main line, but was under a cloud for a while because of the sophisticated 'Voronozeh' variation that we see here.  Still ...cd is the fun, fighting line  and here I offer a little known, but high scoring way of combating it. }
5... cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1 O-O 9. b3
{ This is the Voronezh tabia.  It is very popular with White players who have bothered to learn some Alekhine's theory.  Which at the lower levels seems to be almost nobody.  Out of 42,000 games played by 1600 rated players at blitz on lichess, only 16  (!)  reached this position.  However, White's score of 65% is a little alarming, so it is best to have some idea of what to do.  White's idea is to nix Black's natural play.  ...d5 loses a pawn after c5, Nc6 runs into d5.  Bf5 is most common these days, while ...e5 is probably soundest if followed up correctly - but the abysmal score shows that rarely happens.  Instead, ...a5 is very rare and perhaps a little suspect. But it is noticeable how well it has scored.  And it is that sort of repertoire. }
9... a5 10. Be2
{ Nf3 and Be2 are coming; this order cuts out ...Bg4 for a move. } 10... a4 11.
Nf3 axb3 12. axb3 Bg4 13. O-O d5 { So, we get in our ...d5 after all } 14. c5
Nc8 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3
{ White wins the bishops pair but Black's remaining bishop is good and we keep the position blocked.  The mobile White queenside pawns are a bit of a concern... }
16... e6 17. b4 Ne7 18. b5
{ Instead, White can play g4 to prevent Nf5, but Black gets to play Nc6 and meet b5 with N-a5-c4. }
18... Nf5 19. Qd2 Qh4 { It is important not to take on e3 too early. } 20. Rfd1
h5 21. Ne2 { Danger!  White is now threatening Bg5 } 21... Nxe3 22. fxe3 Nd7
{ A rich and almost unexplored position.  If White now plays Qe1 we happily swap queens.  Otherwise, we will probably play Qe7 and slide our rook down the a file.  But if you are feeling frisky - for example against 23 c6 bc  24 bc Nf6, you can start some kingside play with g5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Playing against e4:  The Alekhine"]
[Black "The Naive exchange variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nf3
{ This is the exchange variation 'as she is played' at the lower levels.  While still more or less respectable  (and pretty common)  , Black has a nice plus score here. }
6... g6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Be3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Bg4 11. h3 { Oh dear! } 11...
Bxf3 12. gxf3 { Bxf3 simply loses the c pawn. } 12... e5
{ Black is winning.  His next move will probably be a knight move - 13 de is met by Nxe5; 13 d5 is met by Nd4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Playing against e4:  The Alekhine"]
[Black "The Naive exchange variation, main line"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nf3
{ This is the exchange variation 'as she is played' at the lower levels.  While still more or less respectable  (and pretty common)  , Black has a nice plus score here. }
6... g6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Be3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Bg4 11. b3 d5
{ Again, emphasising how anti theoretical this opening is at lower levels.  My main database has over 400 examples of this position, with Black scoring a very nice 66%.  But in the opening explorer on lichess, with players averaging 1600 playing blitz, we find precisely 2  (!)  games that make it this far.  11...d5 is the big idea here, but somehow, if you don't know it, it doesn't make it onto the radar. }
12. c5 { cd Nxd5 is just a grotty isolated queen pawn position for White. }
12... Nc8 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 e6 15. Qd2 N8e7 16. Ne2 Nf5 17. b4
{ Often Black will meet b4 with ...a6.  But in this position, even better is.. }
17... b6
{ Black is better here. He will take on c5 and the White d pawn remains a problem, or if White arranges dc, Black dominate in the centre; for example 18 Rab1 bc 19 dc? Ne5. }
*

