1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. a4
{ In most lines of the Alekhine we will meet a4 with a5.  Here White has a tactical try - rare, but worth knowing the antidote. }
7... a5 8. c5 dxc5 9. Bb5+ N6d7 10. Bf4 Bg7 11. Nd5 Na6
{ very uncommon, but mentioned by John Cox as a complete solution - and he seems to be right. }
12. Bxa6 e5 { The key - absolutely forced. } 13. Bb5 exf4 14. Qe2+ Kf8
{ Black is fine here.  He can soon finish his development with Bf6 and Kg7. } *

