[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Playing against e4:  The Alekhine"]
[Black "Alekhines Main Line: Sneaky variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Nb6
{ A rare, cunning move which scores very well.  The idea is clever:  White should meet 4..g6 with Bc4! - so we preempt him!  This line cuts out the need for a lot of theory. White will often play an early ed and have nothing better than some form of exchange variation.  There is an issue though:  the rarely played, but critical 5 a4! }
5. Bd3
{ 5 ed is most common.  This is perhaps second most common at low levels.  It is logical and could be dangerous against lax play, but we can more or less neutralise it with a few precise moves. }
5... g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. Re1 O-O 8. h3 dxe5 9. dxe5 Nc6 10. Nc3 Nb4
{ If the bishop on d3 moves then Qxd1 and maybe Bf5 and the White queenside is very hard to defend. }
11. a4 Nxd3 12. cxd3 Nd5
{ Black can finish development with Be6 or b6, Bb7.  White may have a theoretical small edge, but in practice Black should have good chances. }
*

