1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Nb6 5. a4
{ Nothing is for free... and this is the drawback to the sneaky variation. After provoking a5, White has a variety of dangerous attacking tries.  Fortunately all of these are pretty rare, especially at the lower levels. }
5... a5 6. Nc3 g6 7. exd6 cxd6 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. h4 h6
{ We probably shouldn't allow White to simply play h5, but playing h5 ourselves also weakens our position.  This is probably the best compromise, though it does allow a dangerous piece  sacrifice. }
10. h5 g5 11. O-O Bg7 12. Re1 O-O 13. Nxg5 hxg5 14. Bxg5 f6 15. Be3 f5 16. Ne2
Nd5 17. Bc4 e6 18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Nf4 Nc6 20. c3 Qf6 21. Nxd5 Qf7
{ Black is more or less ok here - and still has an extra bishop. } *

