1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Nb6 5. a4
{ Nothing is for free... and this is the drawback to the sneaky variation. After provoking a5, White has a variety of dangerous attacking tries.  Fortunately all of these are pretty rare, especially at the lower levels. }
5... a5 6. Bb5+ { More common than Nc3, but less  dangerous. } 6... c6 7. Bd3
dxe5 8. Nxe5 { de is not very challenging; Black can just develop normally. }
8... g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. c3 Bxe5
{ Unexpected, but important. White is better if both sides just develop normally. }
11. dxe5 Bf5 12. Bxf5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 gxf5 14. Be3 N8d7 15. Nd2 Nd5 16. Nc4 Rg8
{ Black should be fine here.  He can get some kingside play with ...f4 and ...h5 and make his king safe with K-d8-c7 }
