[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White plays d4, c4: The a6 Indian."]
[Black "1 d4, 2 c4: Introduction."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
{ Welcome to the d4 main lines section of the book.  I offer a Benko approach, though with particular emphasis on attacking the centre with ...Bb7 and ...e6.  This will be possible in most, but not all positions examined.  The modern Benko has been the subject of 2 recent works - a book by Perunovic and a Chessable repertoire by Chess Explained.  Both are excellent, and I have consulted them heavily - but with the aim of not simply repeating their material.  Wherever possible I have given alternatives to the lines suggested in those works, while still maintaining a broadly similar spirit.  I also offer a nice move order trick, that was originally going to be my main recommendation:  1 d4 Nf6  2 c4 a6!?   3 Nc3 c5  4 d5 b5  5 cb - and White has found himself in the Zaitsev variation of the Benko.  Even the White players that allow Benkos normally play another line, so it is not surprising that players who reach the position via this order have a dismal score.  However, there are of course issues with ...a6, so my advice is to try it, at least in blitz, but give it up against given opponents once it stops working.  You will still have the main body of the Benko repertoire to fall back on.  Even more than with the Alekhines, a full survey would take up 10 times the number of lines.  Chess Explained's repertoire has around 300 lines.  However, I think I have covered enough to give you at least a good feel for how to play the positions, and some concrete advice against the most critical lines.  Good luck! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White plays d4, c4: The a6 Indian."]
[Black "The Benko accepted"]
[Result "*"]

{ Looking at the stats on the lichess database, it rapidly became clear that the Benko scores well in fast chess at all levels of play.  A bit more research turned up a very early  (if dodgy)  move order trick that doesn't seem to have an established name; I'll call it the 'a6 Indian'.    But to be getting on with, here's a crash course in the Benko proper.  The Benko has changed a lot in the last few years.  The old interpretation was pretty simple:  sound structure and pressure on the a- and b- files in return for a pawn.  Gradually though White found some accurate move orders against this, so it was back to the drawing board.  Modern interpretations are much more dynamic, and often involve direct attacks on White's centre - at the cost of the integrity of our own. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6
{ The new approach, replacing 5...Bxa6 6 Nc3 d6 7 e4 Bxf1 etc. } 6. Nc3 Bg7 7.
e4 O-O 8. Nf3 Qa5 9. Bd2 Bxa6 10. Bxa6 Qxa6 11. Qe2 d6 12. Qxa6 Nxa6
{ This is similar to the 'old' Benko.  The queen exchange helps Black though, and White's pieces are on slightly funny squares.  Black can look forward to putting pressure on the queenside files combined with sending his king's knight round to the queenside or perhaps an e6 break. }
*

