{ Looking at the stats on the lichess database, it rapidly became clear that the Benko scores well in fast chess at all levels of play.  A bit more research turned up a very early  (if dodgy)  move order trick that doesn't seem to have an established name; I'll call it the 'a6 Indian'.    But to be getting on with, here's a crash course in the Benko proper.  The Benko has changed a lot in the last few years.  The old interpretation was pretty simple:  sound structure and pressure on the a- and b- files in return for a pawn.  Gradually though White found some accurate move orders against this, so it was back to the drawing board.  Modern interpretations are much more dynamic, and often involve direct attacks on White's centre - at the cost of the integrity of our own. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3
{ Quite a nasty line to face.  Though White's score after 5...g6 hasn't been particularly scary in practice - 53% for White on my main database, 52% for Black on the lichess one. }
5... g6 { ChessExplained gives ...ab here, with lots and lots of analysis. } 6.
Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. a4 Bb7 9. e4 e6 10. Bc4
{ John Bartholomew's recommendation on his chessable repertoire for d4 players.  Be2 is also common, but will transpose. }
10... axb5 11. Bxb5 exd5 12. exd5 Qe8+
{ The main line thus far has been Re8+ Be3 Ng4, but White seems better.  The computers  (and Perunovic in his latest book)  prefer the queen move. }
13. Be3 Ng4 14. Qe2 { Qd2 allows Bh6. } 14... Na6 15. O-O Nxe3
{ Black seems fine in the messy positions after either 16 Qxe3 Qxe3 17 fe Nb4, or 16 fe Nc7 and 17...Bxc3. }
