[White "White plays d4, c4: The a6 Indian."]
[Black "Benko declined:  4 Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

{ Looking at the stats on the lichess database, it rapidly became clear that the Benko scores well in fast chess at all levels of play.  A bit more research turned up a very early  (if dodgy)  move order trick that doesn't seem to have an established name; I'll call it the 'a6 Indian'.    But to be getting on with, here's a crash course in the Benko proper.  The Benko has changed a lot in the last few years.  The old interpretation was pretty simple:  sound structure and pressure on the a- and b- files in return for a pawn.  Gradually though White found some accurate move orders against this, so it was back to the drawing board.  Modern interpretations are much more dynamic, and often involve direct attacks on White's centre - at the cost of the integrity of our own. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 { As ever with Qc2, the aim is an early c4. } 4.
Qc2 bxc4
{ If you want a less sound, but aggressive line you could investigate Na6 a3 bc here.  It certainly scores well for the hackers.  On the other hand, ...b4 is also a very sensible move. }
5. e4 e6
{ It was never going to be anything else, was it.  Though I was tempted by ..e5. So that it would be something else. }
6. Bxc4 exd5 7. exd5 d6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Nge2 O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Ng3 Nb6 12. b3
Nxc4 13. bxc4 Rb8 14. h3 Re8 15. Bd2 Nd7
{ Also good is 15 ...Rb7.  White has space; we have a bishop pair and a weak c- pawn to aim at.  Ideally Black would like to play B to f6, or  (after Bf8, g6)  N to e5 or b6 and B to a6.  Depending on what White does Black probably can't achieve all his goals, but nonetheless, he is at least equal here; things may be a little fiddly for a few more moves, but he should have good long term prospects. }
