[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White plays d4, c4: The a6 Indian."]
[Black "The a6 Indian"]
[Result "*"]

{ Looking at the stats on the lichess database, it rapidly became clear that the Benko scores well in fast chess at all levels of play.  A bit more research turned up a very early  (if dodgy)  move order trick that doesn't seem to have an established name; I'll call it the 'a6 Indian'.    But to be getting on with, here's a crash course in the Benko proper.  The Benko has changed a lot in the last few years.  The old interpretation was pretty simple:  sound structure and pressure on the a- and b- files in return for a pawn.  Gradually though White found some accurate move orders against this, so it was back to the drawing board.  Modern interpretations are much more dynamic, and often involve direct attacks on White's centre - at the cost of the integrity of our own. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 a6
{ Remember how nice the Zaitsev was for Black?  Wouldn't it be nice to be able to specialise in that, and even better, frequently transpose into it against opponents who normally play something else?  Well, watch this!  This line was going to be my main repertoire recommendation, and I shall probably expand on it later.  It is a gamble for Black though - one with much larger upsides than downsides - but a gamble nonetheless. }
3. Nc3 { White usually plays Nc3, though of course he has many other options. }
3... c5 4. d5 b5 5. cxb5
{ Bingo!  We have move ordered White into a trappy minor line against the Benko.  Games that reach this position via this move order usually go very well for Black.  HOWEVER:  There are a few problems.  See the following "informational" line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White plays d4, c4: The a6 Indian."]
[Black "The a6 Indian: a note on some problems."]
[Result "*"]

{ Looking at the stats on the lichess database, it rapidly became clear that the Benko scores well in fast chess at all levels of play.  A bit more research turned up a very early  (if dodgy)  move order trick that doesn't seem to have an established name; I'll call it the 'a6 Indian'.    But to be getting on with, here's a crash course in the Benko proper.  The Benko has changed a lot in the last few years.  The old interpretation was pretty simple:  sound structure and pressure on the a- and b- files in return for a pawn.  Gradually though White found some accurate move orders against this, so it was back to the drawing board.  Modern interpretations are much more dynamic, and often involve direct attacks on White's centre - at the cost of the integrity of our own. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 a6
{ Remember how nice the Zaitsev was for Black?  Wouldn't it be nice to be able to specialise in that, and even better, frequently transpose into it against opponents who normally play something else?  Well, watch this!  This line was going to be my main repertoire recommendation, and I shall probably expand on it later.  It is a gamble for Black though - one with much larger upsides than downsides - but a gamble nonetheless. }
3. Nc3 { White usually plays Nc3, though of course he has many other options. }
3... c5 4. d5 b5 5. e4
{ This is one problem line - though basically anything where a6 turns out to be weakening or a waste of a tempo will be an issue.  these are not necessarily fatal problems, but they do mean work is needed to make a coherent repertoire from 2...a6 - and that a good understanding of the regular Benko is needed first. }
5... d6
{ I can't make 5...b4  6 Na4! work for Black.  Now we will have a position arising that is as if we had answered Zaitsev's Nc3 with d6?! instead of ab, and we get a much more normal Benko - hence the main repertoire choice. }
6. cxb5 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. a4 O-O 9. Bf4
{ This simply looks like a better Benko for White than he would normally get.  And he will probably cotton onto it after he has fallen for the Zaitsev transposition once or twice.  Nonetheless, the a6 Indian scores very well in speed chess even at very high levels.  Why not give it a go? }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poxy London System"]
[Black "Classical London System:  An Easy Equaliser."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ Ugh.  The London system.  'Like many players, I have been trying to pretend this system does not exist' - Peter Svidler on chess24.  While I wouldn't claim that London system players should all die of the plague, I'm just saying that if they had all died of the plague then we wouldn't have to play against the London system.  That said, there are a number of good lines against it.  It is almost impossible to dissuade a London system player from his favourite line, so I am giving you 4  (!)  possible replies so that you may at least probe for weaknesses in your opponent's repertoire and have a bit of variety in the games. }
2... g6
{ 2...c5 is also a good line and tends to score best on the databases.  White probably has to push with d5 if he wants anything.  This would fit well with our anti d4,c4 lines, but g6 is also a good move and flexible enough to allow a wide variety of plans. }
3. e3
{ This is the old main line.  It is still widely played, but these days 3 Nc3 with the idea of Qd2, OOO and maybe getting in e4 is meant to be more critical.  Our main difficulty in this line is that White is very solid and it is relatively hard to lure him into making positional mistakes. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. h3
{ Almost always played either earlier or in the next move or two.  There are occasional games where White tries to do without it forever, but they are rare. }
6... c5
{ ....c5 lines tend to work out a little better than ...e5 ones, though with a careful move order those are quite playable too, and I give one later. }
7. c3 Nc6
{ In conjunction with the following idea, this seems to be a simple equaliser.  I give the alternatives Be6 and b6 in later lines.  b6 is probably most popular with the top players; Be6 scores best but is maybe a shade dubious, especially if White has avoided h3.  Still, they are all relatively straightforward to learn and London system players are very persistent, so my advice is to learn all of them and alternate your choices. }
8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 Nd5
{ The key idea.  Routine development would also be ok, but may give White a little something.  Instead, we quickly force e5 and then land on f4.  Note that after you play ...cd, it is important to get something going, preferably ....e5.  If you play passively White gets an easy game simply by pressurizing your e pawn. }
10. Bh2 e5 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nbd2 Nf4 13. Bxf4 exf4 14. Re1 Qc7
{ Black is perhaps even slightly better here.  White's queenside is currently more of a target than a strength, while the f4 pawn is safe and even mildly cramping. In the meantime, Black develops easily while White's looks a little awkward. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poxy London System"]
[Black "Classical London System:  Reversed Reti"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ Ugh.  The London system.  'Like many players, I have been trying to pretend this system does not exist' - Peter Svidler on chess24.  While I wouldn't claim that London system players should all die of the plague, I'm just saying that if they had all died of the plague then we wouldn't have to play against the London system.  That said, there are a number of good lines against it.  It is almost impossible to dissuade a London system player from his favourite line, so I am giving you 4  (!)  possible replies so that you may at least probe for weaknesses in your opponent's repertoire and have a bit of variety in the games. }
2... g6
{ 2...c5 is also a good line and tends to score best on the databases.  White probably has to push with d5 if he wants anything.  This would fit well with our anti d4,c4 lines, but g6 is also a good move and flexible enough to allow a wide variety of plans. }
3. e3
{ This is the old main line.  It is still widely played, but these days 3 Nc3 with the idea of Qd2, OOO and maybe getting in e4 is meant to be more critical.  Our main difficulty in this line is that White is very solid and it is relatively hard to lure him into making positional mistakes. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. h3
{ Almost always played either earlier or in the next move or two.  There are occasional games where White tries to do without it forever, but they are rare. }
6... c5
{ ....c5 lines tend to work out a little better than ...e5 ones, though with a careful move order those are quite playable too, and I give one later. }
7. c3 b6
{ More sophisticated than the first line, though not necessarily better.  Very popular with stronger players, and Black tends to score well, though the computers tend to slightly prefer White.  One drawback is that it can easily lead to a lot of exchanges after an eventual ...Ne4 Nxe4 Bxe4 Bf3. }
8. O-O Bb7 9. Nbd2 Nbd7
{ Nc6 is also playable but this is more common and probably slightly better. }
10. a4 a6
{ An important little move - the idea is to meet a5 with ...b5.  Don't forget though, this will slightly weaken your c5 pawn and start to wake White's dark square bishop. }
11. Bh2 Ra7
{ Black has a variety of plans to maneuver here.  Ra7 is popular and scores well.  The basic idea is Qa8; from there Black can play Bc6  (or Ne4, Nxe4 Bxe4)  to get the rook back into play and he is well placed to fight for the long light diagonal and the c file. }
12. Qb3 Qa8 13. Rfd1
{ In this position, 13...Bc6, 13...h6 and 13...Ne4 have all scored well for Black.  Ne4 is perhaps the safest, Bc6 the most combative. }
*

