[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poxy London System"]
[Black "The London system with Nc3 (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is much more vicious and than the old e3 main line.  Given the chance, White will hit us with e4, and it is best to prevent it, or we end up in a rather nasty line of the Pirc. }
3... d5
{ We can also use this system against 1 d4 Nf6  2 Nc3 Nf6  3 Bf4, the Jobava system.  I suspect 3...a6 is the best move there, but the lines I give here are perfectly playable.  
3...d5 is played to prevent e4.  In practice, you will often simply play Bg7 in blitz even if you know the d5 move.  This is almost certainly a mistake, but I'll give an emergency line to try to limit the damage later. }
4. Qd2 Bg7 5. Bh6
{ White is aiming for a typical anti fianchetto attack with Bh6, h4 h5, Bxg7, maybe OOO etc.  We can try to dodge it by refusing to castle, but it turns out our best reply is to castle into it and fight back vigorously in the centre. }
5... O-O 6. Bxg7 Kxg7 7. O-O-O c5
{ ...c6 with the idea of b5, b4, a5 a4 is a  (probably inferior)  alternative.  ...c5 sets up threats of both cd and c4.  If you haven't already, I strongly urge you to check out the chessable book Bachman v Pragananda for a super Black win. }
8. e3 Qa5
{ Although rarely played yet, this is probably an improvement on the immediate Nc6.  White can take our pawn on c5, so we defend it!   Meanwhile, Qa5 is quite a nice attacking gesture in its own right. }
9. dxc5 Qxc5 10. h3
{ 10.Nxd5??  loses a piece to  Rd8  11.e4  - or  11. c4 Rxd5  -  11...Nxe4   When one of my 7 year old students reached this position he surprised me by going for h3 and g4.  At first it looks odd  (one expects h4 - Raaaaaa!!)  , but it is actually quite logical.  g4, g5 kicking th defensive knight and maybe winning the d pawn.  The engines also like this idea.  The trouble  (for White)  is that we don't mind playing Ne4.  Indeed, we jump before we are pushed. }
10... Nc6 11. g4 Ne4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ne2 Be6
{ Black should be fine here.  An obvious plan is rooks to d8 and c8; but he also has the f5 break which may be even better. }
*

