[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is much more vicious and than the old e3 main line.  Given the chance, White will hit us with e4, and it is best to prevent it, or we end up in a rather nasty line of the Pirc. }
3... d5
{ We can also use this system against 1 d4 Nf6  2 Nc3 Nf6  3 Bf4, the Jobava system.  I suspect 3...a6 is the best move there, but the lines I give here are perfectly playable.  
3...d5 is played to prevent e4.  In practice, you will often simply play Bg7 in blitz even if you know the d5 move.  This is almost certainly a mistake, but I'll give an emergency line to try to limit the damage later. }
4. Qd2 Bg7 5. Bh6
{ White is aiming for a typical anti fianchetto attack with Bh6, h4 h5, Bxg7, maybe OOO etc.  We can try to dodge it by refusing to castle, but it turns out our best reply is to castle into it and fight back vigorously in the centre. }
5... O-O 6. h4
{ You'll find you get this a lot.  It's not so bad, providing Bxg7 follows.  And it is logical - White  keeps his bishop on h6 for a move to rule out ....h5. }
6... c5 7. h5
{ Bxg7 was the only move here.  Let's look at some alternatives to see how they fail.  h5 loses very quickly here. }
7... cxd4 8. Nd1 { This is even worse than I originally thought. } 8... Ne4
{ I originally gave  8...Bxh6  9.Qxh6  e5  here, but throwing in  Ne4  (turns out to be much stronger) }
9. Qc1 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 g5 11. f3 Qa5+ 12. c3 dxc3 13. bxc3 Rd8 14. fxe4 dxe4 15.
e3 Rd6 16. Qxd6 exd6
{ We have won White's queen for rook and knight.  Both sides' developments are comical.    Stockfish's evaluation of better than '-7' for Black may seem surprising.  The key seems to be that Black's knight will be so strong on  c5  or  e5  ,  dominating the board from either square and looking at the  d3  square.  The next few moves are 'sample play'. }
17. a4 Nd7 18. Ne2 Qe5 19. Ra2 Nc5
{ Now  20.Nd4  cant be met by  Qg3+.  White is getting crushed either way. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poxy London System"]
[Black "Nc3 London system.  The h pawn punt Fail (3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is much more vicious and than the old e3 main line.  Given the chance, White will hit us with e4, and it is best to prevent it, or we end up in a rather nasty line of the Pirc. }
3... d5
{ We can also use this system against 1 d4 Nf6  2 Nc3 Nf6  3 Bf4, the Jobava system.  I suspect 3...a6 is the best move there, but the lines I give here are perfectly playable.  
3...d5 is played to prevent e4.  In practice, you will often simply play Bg7 in blitz even if you know the d5 move.  This is almost certainly a mistake, but I'll give an emergency line to try to limit the damage later. }
4. Qd2 Bg7 5. Bh6
{ White is aiming for a typical anti fianchetto attack with Bh6, h4 h5, Bxg7, maybe OOO etc.  We can try to dodge it by refusing to castle, but it turns out our best reply is to castle into it and fight back vigorously in the centre. }
5... O-O 6. h4
{ You'll find you get this a lot.  It's not so bad, providing Bxg7 follows.  And it is logical - White  keeps his bishop on h6 for a move to rule out ....h5. }
6... c5 7. dxc5
{ We are sacrificing a pawn - and ...cd is a threat - so White tries taking it. }
7... Bxh6
{ The counter intuitive Bxh6 features a lot in these lines.  It looks like it accelerates White's attack, but really it just drags his queen away from the action, and if White doesn't manage to regain the initiative his queen actually turns pout to be a target on h6.    It is much better than  7...d4  - though that is still winning - which can be met by  8.Bxg7  Kxg7  - not  dxc3 QxQ  9.Nd1 }
8. Qxh6 d4 9. O-O-O
{ This is a blunder  (the knight should move)  but very natural - and White is lost either way. }
9... Ng4
{ We want to protect the d- pawn before playing Qa5, and kicking the White queen out is a nice bonus. }
10. Qf4 e5 11. Qg3 Qa5 { Unpinning, and so hitting the knight. } 12. Nd5 Qxa2
{ Hitting the knight again - but sacrificing a piece to a small combination. }
13. Ne7+ Kg7 14. Nxc8 Rxc8 15. Qxg4 Na6
{ White's script is being played out in reverse. Black has sacrificed a piece - but has a winning attack. }
16. Rh3
{ White's best try.  Black has a variety of wins here.  The following is accurate, brutal and funny. }
16... Rxc5 17. Ra3 Rxc2+ 18. Kxc2 Nb4+ 19. Kc1 Qc4+ 20. Kd2 Qc2+ 21. Ke1 Qxb2
22. f3 Nc2+ 23. Kf2 Qxa3
{ You have to admire White's development.  Wonder if he will allow the fork on e3?  Either way, Black is totally winning. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poxy London System"]
[Black "Nc3 London system.  The h pawn punt Fail (4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is much more vicious and than the old e3 main line.  Given the chance, White will hit us with e4, and it is best to prevent it, or we end up in a rather nasty line of the Pirc. }
3... d5
{ We can also use this system against 1 d4 Nf6  2 Nc3 Nf6  3 Bf4, the Jobava system.  I suspect 3...a6 is the best move there, but the lines I give here are perfectly playable.  
3...d5 is played to prevent e4.  In practice, you will often simply play Bg7 in blitz even if you know the d5 move.  This is almost certainly a mistake, but I'll give an emergency line to try to limit the damage later. }
4. Qd2 Bg7 5. Bh6
{ White is aiming for a typical anti fianchetto attack with Bh6, h4 h5, Bxg7, maybe OOO etc.  We can try to dodge it by refusing to castle, but it turns out our best reply is to castle into it and fight back vigorously in the centre. }
5... O-O 6. h4
{ You'll find you get this a lot.  It's not so bad, providing Bxg7 follows.  And it is logical - White  keeps his bishop on h6 for a move to rule out ....h5. }
6... c5 7. Bxg7
{ The correct move, and White normally manages to find it.  If he isn't worried about...h5, then getting rid of the bishop on g7 as soon as possible makes sense. }
7... Kxg7 8. h5
{ But this punt is overoptimistic.  Taking the h pawn with the knight is good for White after OOO or dc.  But we have a much better pawn to take. }
8... cxd4 { The fact that he is now losing doesn't usually bother White yet. }
9. Qxd4
{ Simply taking on g6 then playing Qh6+ doesn't actually get anywhere after Kg8:  9 hg cd  10 Qh6+ Kg8  (NOT Kh8?? g7+!)  11 gh+ Kh8 12 bc Bf5.  Qxd4 is the relatively best try, recapturing the pawn and pretending he is not losing a tempo by swining round to h4. }
9... Nc6 10. Qh4 d4 11. O-O-O Qa5
{ Same old story:  White's attack isn't getting through, his knight is en prise and if it moves we can take on a2. }
12. hxg6
{ If Knight e4 we just take on e4, and then on g6 with the f pawn.  In these Bxg7 lines we typically have to answer hg with fg. }
12... fxg6 13. Rxd4 { Throwing in Qh6+ Kf7 only makes things worse. } 13...
Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Be6 15. Nf3
{ N f3   h3  - g5 is often the correct way of following up the first wave of these Bh6, h4 attacks.  But it is too slow here.  And en prise on g5 unless W plays Qh4 first   If instead a3, we have a nice sequence Rad8 Qh4 Rc8! winning. }
15... Bxa2
{ White's attack has failed.  Black is fully developed and can defend with Bg8 if needed, but by this stage he will probably be too busy pursuing an attack of his own. }
*

