1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is much more vicious and than the old e3 main line.  Given the chance, White will hit us with e4, and it is best to prevent it, or we end up in a rather nasty line of the Pirc. }
3... d5 4. e3
{ White mixes the e3 and Nc3 systems.  I have sometimes heard this called the Aronian system.  It is quite dangerous if we are unprepared - and also the most common line of play. }
4... Bg7 5. Nb5
{ This rules out ...c5 for a while but doesn't really achieve much.  h4! is the main line, and more dangerous. }
5... Na6 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8. Nc3 Qb6 { Already probably a Black edge. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poxy London System"]
[Black "Nc3 London system. The hybrid hack 8 Nb5?! and instant rook grab"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is much more vicious and than the old e3 main line.  Given the chance, White will hit us with e4, and it is best to prevent it, or we end up in a rather nasty line of the Pirc. }
3... d5 4. e3
{ White mixes the e3 and Nc3 systems.  I have sometimes heard this called the Aronian system.  It is quite dangerous if we are unprepared - and also the most common line of play. }
4... Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ This makes a lot of sense here.  5 ... OO is a bit cooperative - White gets on with it with h5.  5 ... c5 looks natural, but after c5 , Nb5 really is annoying:  Black plays Na6, White Be2 and he is set for h5 again, while evicting the knight on b5 will  be very  difficult.  5...c6 is a reasonable alternative.  However, 6 h5 remains a dangerous punt, while the simpler Be2, Nf3 leaves Black a little passive and he will probably have to play ...h6 or ...h5 anyway. }
6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2 c5 8. Nb5
{ Thematic after ...c5.  But we can defuse it, not by Na6, but by offering the exchange.  This hardly seems to have been played, but seems very strong. }
8... cxd4 9. Nc7 Ng4 { ...e5 is also pretty good here too. } 10. Nxa8 e5 11.
Bxe5 { If instead Bg5, ...f6 is forced - but good. } 11... Bxe5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5
13. exd4 Ng4
{ Black is an exchange and a pawn down.  However, the knight on a8 is trapped and Black will finish his development very quickly and attack before White is ready.  Black is significantly better here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poxy London System"]
[Black "Nc3 London system. The hybrid hack Nb5?! White stabilises the centre"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3
{ This is much more vicious and than the old e3 main line.  Given the chance, White will hit us with e4, and it is best to prevent it, or we end up in a rather nasty line of the Pirc. }
3... d5 4. e3
{ White mixes the e3 and Nc3 systems.  I have sometimes heard this called the Aronian system.  It is quite dangerous if we are unprepared - and also the most common line of play. }
4... Bg7 5. h4 h5
{ This makes a lot of sense here.  5 ... OO is a bit cooperative - White gets on with it with h5.  5 ... c5 looks natural, but after c5 , Nb5 really is annoying:  Black plays Na6, White Be2 and he is set for h5 again, while evicting the knight on b5 will  be very  difficult.  5...c6 is a reasonable alternative.  However, 6 h5 remains a dangerous punt, while the simpler Be2, Nf3 leaves Black a little passive and he will probably have to play ...h6 or ...h5 anyway. }
6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2 c5 8. Nb5
{ Thematic after ...c5.  But we can defuse it, not by Na6, but by offering the exchange.  This hardly seems to have been played, but seems very strong. }
8... cxd4 9. exd4
{ White stabilizes the centre before proceeding.  We could chicken out with Na6, but the following is stronger. }
9... Nc6 10. Nc7 Rb8
{ ...e5 works well here and may even be objectively a little stronger.  But this is fun. }
11. Nb5 Bf5 { You want my rook?  Fine!  I don't care! } 12. Bxb8 Qxb8
{ Black is at least a little better, despite the material deficit.  He will play moves like Ng4, Be4, a6 and e5.  I must admit, it might be just a little difficult to believe Black has full compensation here.  But if in doubt, play around with the line a little on your computer.  Or better still, against your human blitz opponents. }
*

