[Black "Another Bd3 blunder"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ Ugh.  The London system.  'Like many players, I have been trying to pretend this system does not exist' - Peter Svidler on chess24.  While I wouldn't claim that London system players should all die of the plague, I'm just saying that if they had all died of the plague then we wouldn't have to play against the London system.  That said, there are a number of good lines against it.  It is almost impossible to dissuade a London system player from his favourite line, so I am giving you 4  (!)  possible replies so that you may at least probe for weaknesses in your opponent's repertoire and have a bit of variety in the games. }
2... g6
{ 2...c5 is also a good line and tends to score best on the databases.  White probably has to push with d5 if he wants anything.  This would fit well with our anti d4,c4 lines, but g6 is also a good move and flexible enough to allow a wide variety of plans. }
3. e3
{ This is the old main line.  It is still widely played, but these days 3 Nc3 with the idea of Qd2, OOO and maybe getting in e4 is meant to be more critical.  Our main difficulty in this line is that White is very solid and it is relatively hard to lure him into making positional mistakes. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. Bd3
{ Not really the right square for the bishop in this line.  Be2 is better. }
5... O-O 6. O-O c5
{ Bd3 can be vulnerable to the plan of Qe8 and e5 as we saw earlier. But it also has pitfalls against our standard ...c5  plan, especially the "easy equaliser" version. }
7. c3 Nc6 8. Nbd2 cxd4 9. exd4 e5
{ With the bishop on e2 we had to prepare this with Nd5.  Here we can play it  (with advantage)  immediately.  Note - we haven't even needed White to waste time on h3. }
10. dxe5
{ White should play  10.Bg5  after which he is merely worse. But in speed chess they often blitz out the following, which doesn't win a pawn, but loses a piece. }
10... dxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Qxd3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poxy London System"]
[Black "I find your lack of h3 disturbing."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ Ugh.  The London system.  'Like many players, I have been trying to pretend this system does not exist' - Peter Svidler on chess24.  While I wouldn't claim that London system players should all die of the plague, I'm just saying that if they had all died of the plague then we wouldn't have to play against the London system.  That said, there are a number of good lines against it.  It is almost impossible to dissuade a London system player from his favourite line, so I am giving you 4  (!)  possible replies so that you may at least probe for weaknesses in your opponent's repertoire and have a bit of variety in the games. }
2... g6
{ 2...c5 is also a good line and tends to score best on the databases.  White probably has to push with d5 if he wants anything.  This would fit well with our anti d4,c4 lines, but g6 is also a good move and flexible enough to allow a wide variety of plans. }
3. e3
{ This is the old main line.  It is still widely played, but these days 3 Nc3 with the idea of Qd2, OOO and maybe getting in e4 is meant to be more critical.  Our main difficulty in this line is that White is very solid and it is relatively hard to lure him into making positional mistakes. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. O-O
{ You may have noticed that in all the lines I have given so far, White plays the move h3, mainly to give his dark squared bishop a hidey hole.  This tempo can be a key to the efficacy of some of Black's defences.  The grandmaster favourite with b6 doesn't suffer much; Black has lots of useful moves, he's not going for an early confrontation and White usually ends up playing h3 anyway.  But for others, eg the Be6 special, White's accelerated development hurts us; the line just doesnt work as well.  However.  Black now has the option of chasing down the White dark square bishop.  The positions get messy but Black scores surprisingly well.  Note:  This works best if White has castled  (but is still usually legitimate in other positions)  .  The following is a very common sequence. }
6... c5
{ We let White revert to normal lines for another move; he often plays h3 here... }
7. c3 { But now it is all systems go. } 7... Nh5
{ For years I thought this rather played into White's hands, but when researching I was pleasantly surprised. This is analytically sound, and move massively outscores the alternatives on lichess. }
8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Nfd2
{ This is White's "trick". If he just plays  10.Bg3  Nxg3  Black is comfortably better. }
10... gxh4
{ We have the counter sacrifice  10...Nf4?!  here, but I don't think it is as good. }
11. Bxh5 h3
{ Black has lots of good moves here; turning the h- pawn into a nuisance looks like a good start, but our main aim will be central breaks. }
12. g3 Nd7 13. Bf3 e5
{ Most forcing, though  13...Nf6  14.Na3  Be6  is also good. } 14. Ne4 exd4 15.
exd4 { 15.Nxd6?!  Ne5  is =+ } 15... cxd4 16. cxd4 Nb8
{ 16...Nb6  or  Nf6  are fine as well of course. } 17. Nbc3 Nc6
{ It is as if a million voice that thought omitting h3 cried out in pain and were suddenly silenced. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Poxy London System"]
[Black "Happy birthday!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ Ugh.  The London system.  'Like many players, I have been trying to pretend this system does not exist' - Peter Svidler on chess24.  While I wouldn't claim that London system players should all die of the plague, I'm just saying that if they had all died of the plague then we wouldn't have to play against the London system.  That said, there are a number of good lines against it.  It is almost impossible to dissuade a London system player from his favourite line, so I am giving you 4  (!)  possible replies so that you may at least probe for weaknesses in your opponent's repertoire and have a bit of variety in the games. }
2... g6
{ 2...c5 is also a good line and tends to score best on the databases.  White probably has to push with d5 if he wants anything.  This would fit well with our anti d4,c4 lines, but g6 is also a good move and flexible enough to allow a wide variety of plans. }
3. e3
{ This is the old main line.  It is still widely played, but these days 3 Nc3 with the idea of Qd2, OOO and maybe getting in e4 is meant to be more critical.  Our main difficulty in this line is that White is very solid and it is relatively hard to lure him into making positional mistakes. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. c4
{ Instead of ultra solidity with c3, White is a little more ambitious and plays something which resembles a main line d4 opening.  White has held back with this move until after we have played ...d6; if he plays it earlier, ...d5 is a serious and sensible option. }
5... O-O
{ Nh5 probably isn't bad here but I am mostly staying away from those lines in this repertoire. }
6. Nc3 c5 7. h3 cxd4
{ Qa5 is also interesting here.  It scores well but I don't currently trust it. }
8. exd4 { 8.Nxd4  e5  will probably only happen in bullet. } 8... d5
{ Soon after I published the original variation, Peter Svidler defended it on a chess 24.  The 6th birthday banter blitz, starting at the 26 min mark  .  He rapidly got in trouble, which was a bit concerning.  Fortunately, there is a good solution. }
9. c5 { A common move, and the choice of Svidler's opponent. } 9... b6
{ Svidler played the very natural  9...Nc6?!  , but this is better. } 10. b4
{ 10.cxb6  Qxb6  is obviously very nice for Black. } 10... Ne4
{ Who wanted to play the standard looking  10...a5?  here? White would be better after  11.Na4!  But instead, the star move  Ne4!  is very strong. }
11. Rc1 bxc5 12. bxc5 Nc6 13. Be2 Qa5 14. Qa4
{ 14.Bd2  Nxd2  is miserable, but probably better. } 14... Qxa4 15. Nxa4 Nxd4
{ Do you like developing pieces, or stealing pawns?  15...Bd7  is of roughly equal strength here. }
16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. O-O e5 { 17...g5  can be played too, with a similar idea. }
18. Be3 Bxe3 19. fxe3 Ng3 20. Rfe1 Nxe2+ 21. Rxe2 Be6
{ Black is a pawn up, with various positional advantages.  While work still has to be done, this should actually already be winning. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English:  ...g6 systems."]
[Black "Botvinnik Variation.  9...f4!"]
[Result "*"]

{ The English opening  (and even more so, 1 Nf3)  present all the usual challenges with Black - how to play soundly but retain winning chances - while adding a different problem - how to avoid being tricked into lines you don't normally play against the queen pawn if White plays an early d4.  1...g6 is a good move for Modern, King's Indian, Benoni, Benko, Benoni and Grunfeld players.  And it is good for our main anti English system - the closed Sicilian reversed.  However, 1 c4 g6  2 d4 would leave our anti d4 repertoire, so I am opting for the  1...e5 move order here. }
1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7
{ This is one of the critical tries for White - the Botvinnik system.  It is pretty popular and a lot of players play 'Botvinnik against everything'.  If you come across one of those guys, I can also recommend a line of the symmetrical English - see later.  In the ...e5, ...g6 lines, White's system works really well if Black skips f5 and simply plays Nf6.  Lines where Black gets ...f5 in first are a lot more respectable  (and better scoring)  but can still be a little tricky to handle.  I have summarized the main line below; but while researching I came across the following nice twist on move 9.  It is almost unknown, and nobody seems to have played the critical line against it.  Whilst I'm not sure I'd fully trust it in a high level correspondence game, I'd be quite happy over the board and very happy in blitz. }
5. e4 d6 6. Nge2 f5 7. d3 Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd5 f4
{ The star move.  Black sacrifices a pawn  (or two)  to start an attack right out of the opening. }
10. gxf4 { Or Nxf6 Qxf6 and Black is slightly better } 10... Nh5 11. Kh1
{ This seems to be the critical test - but I can't find anyone who has actually  played it!  It is still an excellent illustration of the main ideas, so what you are likely to get in practice will be similar to this, but better. }
11... Qh4 12. f5 gxf5 13. Nxc7 Rb8 14. Ng3 Nf4 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf4 exf4 17.
exf5 Kh8 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Ne6 Be5
{ Much better than simply taking on f5 straight away.  The threat is ...f3, splat! }
20. Qf3 Rxf5
{ White is a pawn up.  Black has perhaps half a pawn's compensation.  But White's position is very tricky in practice - and unless he has read this book he is very unlikely to make it this far. }
*

