[White "The English:  ...g6 systems."]
[Black "Botvinnik Variation.  Main line."]
[Result "*"]

{ The English opening  (and even more so, 1 Nf3)  present all the usual challenges with Black - how to play soundly but retain winning chances - while adding a different problem - how to avoid being tricked into lines you dont normally play against the queen pawn if White plays an early d4.  1...g6 is a good move for Modern, King's Indian, Benoni, Benko, Benoni and Grunfeld players.  And it is good for our main anti English system - the closed Sicilian reversed.  However, 1 c4 g6  2 d4 would leave our anti d4 repertoire, so I am opting for the  1...e5 move order here. }
1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7
{ This is one of the critical tries for White - the Botvinnik system.  It is pretty popular and a lot of players play 'Botvinnik against everything'.  If you come across one of those guys, I can also recommend a line of the symmetrical English - see later.  In the ...e5, ...g6 lines, White's system works really well if Black skips f5 and simply plays Nf6.  Lines where Black gets ...f5 in first are a lot more respectable  (and better scoring)  but can still be a little tricky to handle.  I have summarized the main line below; but while researching I came across the following nice twist on move 9.  It is almost unknown, and nobody seems to have played the critical line against it.  Whilst I'm not sure I'd fully trust it in a high level correspondence game, I'd be quite happy over the board and very happy in blitz. }
5. e4 d6 6. Nge2 f5 7. d3 Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd5 Be6
{ The main line.  Sounder than ...f4 but less fun. } 10. Bg5 Qd7 11. Qd2
{ Black has a variety of moves here:  11...Nh5, 11...Rae8, 11...Rf7,  11...Kh8, or even the odd looking ...11 fe.  Personally I'm not thrilled by Black's position here but it is perfectly respectable - commonly played at master level and with normal statistics for wins, draws and losses. }
