[Black "Closed Sicilian Reversed with d3"]
[Result "*"]

{ The English opening  (and even more so, 1 Nf3)  present all the usual challenges with Black - how to play soundly but retain winning chances - while adding a different problem - how to avoid being tricked into lines you dont normally play against the queen pawn if White plays an early d4.  1...g6 is a good move for Modern, King's Indian, Benoni, Benko, Benoni and Grunfeld players.  And it is good for our main anti English system - the closed Sicilian reversed.  However, 1 c4 g6  2 d4 would leave our anti d4 repertoire, so I am opting for the  1...e5 move order here. }
1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Nf3 f5 7. O-O h6 8. Rb1 Nf6
9. b4 O-O 10. b5 Ne7 11. Nd2
{ Not the most common, but the most annoying.  Against almost anything else we can play ... Be6 and Qd7. }
11... g5 { Black threatens ...f4 followed up by maybe Nf5 or g4. } 12. Qb3
{ Again, not so common, but "annoyingest" } 12... Kh8 13. Ba3
{ I was a little bit concerned by White's huge score on my main database here, but... }
13... a6 { Seems to solve all Black's problems. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English:  ...g6 systems."]
[Black "Closed Sicilian Reversed with e3"]
[Result "*"]

{ The English opening  (and even more so, 1 Nf3)  present all the usual challenges with Black - how to play soundly but retain winning chances - while adding a different problem - how to avoid being tricked into lines you dont normally play against the queen pawn if White plays an early d4.  1...g6 is a good move for Modern, King's Indian, Benoni, Benko, Benoni and Grunfeld players.  And it is good for our main anti English system - the closed Sicilian reversed.  However, 1 c4 g6  2 d4 would leave our anti d4 repertoire, so I am opting for the  1...e5 move order here. }
1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. e3 d6 6. Nge2 Be6
{ ...h5 plans are especially attractive for Black in these lines, with the White knight on e2.  Indeed, the immediate h5 is interesting and scores well.  But lets stick to the main line. }
7. d3 Qd7 8. Nd5
{ Most common, even though Black isn't really threatening ...d5 yet.  But it prevents ...Bh3 because of Bxh3 Qxh3 Nxc7. }
8... Nd8 9. O-O
{ White can instead play e4, after which c6 Ne3 and then either Bh3 or simply ...Ne7 }
9... c6 10. Ndc3 Bh3 11. d4
{ White has to break in the centre or get hacked up by ...h5. } 11... Bxg2 12.
Kxg2 exd4 13. exd4 d5 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Re1 Ne7 16. Bg5 Ndc6
{ This is equal and pretty drawish, but if anything, I'd rather have Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English:  ...g6 systems."]
[Black "c5 v the Botvinnik; a common trap."]
[Result "*"]

{ 1.c4  English   and  1.Nf3  players can be a tricky bunch, often prone to fiddling with their move orders, either to specifically try and catch people out or simply because they are making it up as they go along.  My initial aim was to pay very close attention and make a narrow, airtight repertoire which would cover all the possible transpositions.  But such repertoires are very fragile, and on reflection I have decided that it is better to include some common setups, so that you will be more or less familiar with the play no matter what they throw at you. }
1. c4 g6
{ So, lesson 1:  1...g6 is a very strong, flexible move against 1. c4.  You can also play it against 1. Nf3; whether you should do so depends on how you feel about allowing Pirc/modern type positions if they follow up with e4 and d4. }
2. Nc3 Bg7 3. g3 Nf6
{ 3. d6 would allow 4. d4 with a transposition to a fianchetto King's Indian.  Here we are ready to meet 4. d4 with c5 if you don't like that sort of thing. }
4. Bg2 O-O 5. e4
{ When we see this we know that we are probably getting a Botvinnik system.  But they still may play d4 if we let them.  So we don't. }
5... c5
{ Lesson 2:  The Botvinnik system generally scores pretty well against systems where Black plays ... e5  (though of course we have some interesting ideas about that in this repertoire)  ; but Black is pretty comfortable in lines where he has played ...c5. }
6. Nge2 Nc6 7. O-O d6 8. d3
{ Making it official:  White has played the Botvinnik setup. } 8... a6 9. h3
{ Not the only move, but useful, and by far the most common. } 9... Rb8 10. Be3
{ The third most common move; natural, but not terribly good.  Second most common is 10. f4; most common and probably best is holding up our ...b5 move with 10. a4. }
10... b5 { Black's play is smooth and automatic. } 11. Qd2
{ The natural follow up, but pretty bad. } 11... bxc4
{ Black scores 85% from here.  he may already be objectively winning. } 12.
dxc4 { 12 d4 limits the damage but is obviously bad. } 12... Ne5
{ Threatening to win the c- pawn and then the dark square bishop. } 13. b3
{ Several 2500+ rated players have fallen into this trap; meanwhile the lichess database currently has 127 examples. }
13... Bxh3
{ And this was the other threat.  The bishop can't be taken without allowing Nf3+ winning the queen; so White usually lashes out at the offending knight. }
14. f4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Neg4 { Still hunting the bishop. } 16. Bg1 Qc7
{ Black is winning.  A pawn up, but the computer evaluation closer to '-2'. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English:  ...g6 systems."]
[Black "c5 v the Botvinnik; the f4 line."]
[Result "*"]

{ 1.c4  English   and  1.Nf3  players can be a tricky bunch, often prone to fiddling with their move orders, either to specifically try and catch people out or simply because they are making it up as they go along.  My initial aim was to pay very close attention and make a narrow, airtight repertoire which would cover all the possible transpositions. But such repertoires are very fragile, and on reflection I have decided that it is better to include some common setups, so that you will be more or less familiar with the play no matter what they throw at you. }
1. c4 g6
{ So, lesson 1:  1...g6 is a very strong, flexible move against 1. c4.  You can also play it against 1. Nf3; whether you should do so depends on how you feel about allowing Pirc/modern type positions if they follow up with e4 and d4. }
2. Nc3 Bg7 3. g3 Nf6
{ 3. d6 would allow 4. d4 with a transposition to a fianchetto King's Indian.  Here we are ready to meet 4. d4 with c5 if you don't like that sort of thing. }
4. Bg2 O-O 5. e4
{ When we see this we know that we are probably getting a Botvinnik system.  But they still may play d4 if we let them.  So we don't. }
5... c5
{ Lesson 2:  The Botvinnik system generally scores pretty well against systems where Black plays ... e5  (though of course we have some interesting ideas about that in this repertoire)  ; but Black is pretty comfortable in lines where he has played ...c5. }
6. Nge2 Nc6 7. O-O d6 8. d3
{ Making it official:  White has played the Botvinnik setup. } 8... a6 9. h3
{ Not the only move, but useful, and by far the most common. } 9... Rb8 10. f4
{ More common  (and much better than)  the plan with an early Be3/Qd2.  It obviously rules out Ne5! }
10... Bd7
{ Here we have to decide if we want to 'fall into a trap' ourselves.  10...b5  11.e5  dxe5  12.Bxc6  Bxh3  13.Bg2  Bxg2  14.Kxg2  Ng4!  gives us two pawns, a weak White king and activity for the piece - more or less full compensation. But the main line I give here works well without a similar degree of risk. }
11. Be3
{ White can also play a4 here, with play similar to the main 10. a4 line. }
11... b5 12. Qd2 Ne8
{ The key move, which changes the practical scores form 'around even' to '66% for Black  .  White has a wide choice now; will probably play 'Queen's rook somewhere.'  Let's look at a line where he tries to attack on the kingside as quickly as possible. }
13. f5
{ Other alternatives include  13.e5  dxe5  14.Bxc5  Nd6 =   13.Rae1  b4!  14.Nd1  b3!  15.a3  Nd4  16.Ndc3  Nc2  =+ }
13... bxc4 14. dxc4 Ne5 15. b3 a5 16. g4 a4 17. Rab1 Nc7
{ Both sides have their chances, but perhaps a small Black advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English:  ...g6 systems."]
[Black "c5 v the Botvinnik  main line with 10.  a4"]
[Result "*"]

{ 1.c4  English   and  1.Nf3  players can be a tricky bunch, often prone to fiddling with their move orders, either to specifically try and catch people out or simply because they are making it up as they go along.  My initial aim was to pay very close attention and make a narrow, airtight repertoire which would cover all the possible transpositions.  But such repertoires are very fragile, and on reflection I have decided that it is better to include some common setups, so that you will be more or less familiar with the play no matter what they throw at you. }
1. c4 g6
{ So, lesson 1:  1...g6 is a very strong, flexible move against 1. c4.  You can also play it against 1. Nf3; whether you should do so depends on how you feel about allowing Pirc/modern type positions if they follow up with e4 and d4. }
2. Nc3 Bg7 3. g3 Nf6
{ 3. d6 would allow 4. d4 with a transposition to a fianchetto King's Indian.  Here we are ready to meet 4. d4 with c5 if you don't like that sort of thing. }
4. Bg2 O-O 5. e4
{ When we see this we know that we are probably getting a Botvinnik system.  But they still may play d4 if we let them.  So we don't. }
5... c5
{ Lesson 2:  The Botvinnik system generally scores pretty well against systems where Black plays ... e5  (though of course we have some interesting ideas about that in this repertoire)  ; but Black is pretty comfortable in lines where he has played ...c5. }
6. Nge2 Nc6 7. O-O d6 8. d3
{ Making it official:  White has played the Botvinnik setup. } 8... a6 9. h3
{ Not the only move, but useful, and by far the most common. } 9... Rb8 10. a4
{ By far the main line.  White prevents...b5.  But maybe not for very long! }
10... Ne8
{ Again, an almost universal choice among those 'in the know'.  White wants to  play d4, and he knight clears the way for the bishop to help prevent that. Later it can relocate to c7, where it will help fight for ...b5, or continue on its way to e6 and look at d4. }
11. Be3 { Developing, and fighting for d4.  What to do? } 11... e5
{ Well, the first thing to do is notice that White isn't really preventing ...b5 any more at all now!    11...b5  12.axb5  axb5  13.Nxb5  Nc7  , and White can't hang on to the pawn. For example,  14.Nec3  Nxb5  15.cxb5?  Nd4  -/+ This rare line has been very succesful in practice; almost all the master games have been drawn, while Black has scored 75% on lichess!   Most common for Black has been  11...Nc7 ?!  , but the engines and I don't like it at all.  12.d4!  and White achieves his aim - Black can try to hold with  b6!  , or more commonly simply play  12...cxd4  13.Nxd4  Ne6  14.Nde2  Bd7  (!)  (, but in either case Black is  almost  - but not quite equal.  Not a disaster if you are patient, but you run the risk of losing a game where you weren't quite sure where you went wrong, and it seems like unnecessary suffering.)  Our choice, ...e5! has much to recommend it.  It makes sense prepositionally, scores well in practice, and I accidentally left Stockfish 11 running on the position over night and it came out as the engine's recommendation at 54 ply!  (0.00 of course)  . }
12. f4
{ 12.Qd2  Nd4   12.Nd5  is important though:  12...b6!  13.Nec3  Nc7  14.Nxc7  Qxc7  15.Nd5  Qd8  16.Qd2  Be6  17.Bg5  f6  18.Be3  Qd7  , with  ...f5  coming soon. }
12... exf4
{ Standard.  We open up our bishop again, while keeping sufficient control of the centre and preventing White playing f5. }
13. gxf4 { Or  13.Nxf4  Nc7  -/= } 13... f5
{ Or  13...Nd4  with equality.  f5  is riskier but perhaps more fun and has usually been the human choice. The position now has a very 'Closed sicilian' feel to it. White may as well get in  d4  while he can. }
14. d4 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nf6 16. exf5 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Bxf5 18. a5 Kh8 19. Kh2 Qc7 20.
b3 Rbe8
{ Perhaps slightly better for White, but as the cliche goes, 'chances for both sides'.  If you don't like this, then 13... Nd4 is the move for you. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English:  ...g6 systems."]
[Black "Fischer's Zugzwang."]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. d3 d6
{ More move - order proofing.  This position  (and this sequence of moves)  is like the Ruy Lopez, the Najdorf or the Queen's Gambit Declined; popular at all levels, and everyone should know a bit about it as part of their basic chess culture.  Fischer once claimed that the position at move 6 favoured Black.  If White played c4, Black could play e5 with advantage; while if White played c4 Black could play e5 with advantage!  The Russians, to put it politely, were sceptical.  And yet, when I look in most databases I find Fischer seemed to be right - a small black edge in either case.  Black has more information than White by one half move, but I suspect the explanation is simply that the systems tend to be chosen by players more often when they are outrated, and want something straightforward and non bookish - ie the Black players simply outrate the White ones.  But I haven't checked this.  Still, it pays considerably to know a bit more about the position than 6 moves.  We will start with the Englsih version. }
6. c4 e5 7. Nc3 Nc6
{ Variations exist with c6, Nbd7 etc but we will stick with the straightforward , and most popular development.  We have a closed sicilian reversed, but with the Black f- pawn still at home.  We'd much rather it was on f5.  Though in compensation we are a tempo ahead on that line  .  With a White pawn on e3 and his king's knight on e2 this would be pretty unpleasant; with the pawn on e4  (The Botvinnik setup)  Black may already be lost.  But with the pawn on e2 and the knight on f3, things really aren't too bad. }
8. Rb1
{ Almost always played - White wants to expand with b4 - b5, and nab the centeral light squares generally.  Simple. }
8... a5
{ This is a major crunch point.  There are two ways of playing this position - with h6 or Re8.    8...h6  systems are common, but hard to handle. They work best without  a5  thrown in. The dream is something like this:  9.b4  Be6  (the point of h6 was to rule out Ng5 here)  10.b5  Ne7  11.a4  Qd7  12.Re1  Bh3  13.Ng4  Qb3  14.Bh1  f5  and Black has a nice attack - indeed, he is probably better.  And that is indeed the most common sequence of moves, and if you could guarantee you could get it every time I'd have no hesitation recommending it for Black. Unfortunately, White doesn't need to be nearly so co-operative.    For example, what is that pawn on  a4  actually doing? Try replacing that move with  8...h6  9.b4  Be6  10.b5  Ne7  11.Nd2!.  b7  is attacked, so  11...Rb8  -  Qc8  (has similar problems -, and now an early Queen move means that the rook can go to a better square than e1 - for instance d1, preparing)  e3  (and)  d4  (.  In fact, the Queen can go to)  a4  with  12.Qa4  , hitting the a- pawn. Black probably has to play  12...Nc8  , but now  13. Nd5  or  13.Ba3.  This doesn't look fun at all.  The  Re8  system works much better - indeed Black has a plus score. This system does need the inclusion of  ...a5  though. }
9. a3 Re8 10. Bg5
{ Most common, because Black has a trick. If  10.b4?!  axb4  11.axb4  Black has  11...e4!  , which equalises at once. The sort of equality where White scores 30%   And  10.Nd2  is well met by  10...Nd4  11.b4  axb4  12.axb4  c6  13.b5  d5  Bg5 aims to swap off the knight on f6 and fight for the light squares.  No point letting it hang around on  g5  though, it is actually worth a tempi to force White to carry out his plan. }
10... h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Bg7 14. b5 Ne7 15. Qb3 Be6 16. Nd2
c6 { And we have developed and prepared  ....d5  . So we play... } 17. Rfc1 f5
{ It is even better.  Some  advantage to Black. : } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English:  ...g6 systems."]
[Black "Fischer's Zugzwang.  King's Indian Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. d3 d6 6. e4
{ Look ma, a system!  Mmmmmm.  Players love systems.  These guys were like the London system players before the London systems players were uncool.  Except that they didn't just annoy you, they were dangerous as well.  And like most 'systems' it has dedicated followers who love 'their' opening.  So let's see how well White scores as a whole.  48%.  Good.  The King's Indian attack is of course perfectly legitimate and respectable. It just works better against some setups than others.  Here White doesn't have a particularly good form. }
6... c5 { He goes left, we got right, and vice versa. } 7. Nbd2
{ It is much more rare  (but possible)  for White to opt for   7.Nc3  Nc6.  White mostly goes for the  8.h3  plan now - we would meet  8. Re1  (by)  ...e5  . So  8...Rb8  9.Be3  b5  10.Qd2  b4  11.Ne2.  11. Ne1  (is possible too - it guards b2 but blocks the first rank.  Black has done well after)  ...a5  (, with probably)  ...e5  (next.  Now we  don't  play)  11... Re8?!  (, but instead for instance)  11... Bd7  11...a5  or  11...Qa5  12.a3  bxa3  13.Qxa5  Nxa5  14.bxa3  Ba6  =+ }
7... Nc6 8. c3 Rb8
{ At this stage I might be guilty of misleading you a little, or rather, inviting you to take a little gamble. 8... Rb8 is most common here, and scores excellently. Black pretends White isn't threatening d4, and White usually goes along with him, either with Re1  (to 'prepare' it)  or a4  (to stop ...b5)  .    But  8...e5  is actually an excellent move here, and scores very well. The drawback is that it may encourage White not to bother with  Re1  at all. }
9. Re1
{ Instead  9.d4!?  could be critical; but after  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  Bd7!  11.b3  Rc8  12.a3  b5!  , with  ...e5  next, all the engines seem to think Black is fine. }
9... e5
{ It is much more important to clamp the centre than to keep our bishop open. But  9...Nd7  is excellent as well.  Black has done very well from here, partly because half the time White neglects to play a4 and instead "gets on with things" with Nf1. }
10. a4 h6 11. Nc4 Be6 12. Ne3 d5
{ 12...Re8  13.c4  is also pretty reasonable. Play now revolves around gradually preparing  ...b5  or  ...f5.  There can now follow a tactical sequence... }
13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nc4 Qc7 15. Qe2 Rbe8 { It has to be this rook! } 16. Nfxe5
{ An error, but a very complex one!  If White doesn't go for this we will probably play ...f6 next. }
16... Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Qxe5
{ Or  18.c4  Bd7  19.cxd5  Bxg3  20.hxg3  Rxe2  21.Rxe2  - another computer variant with a winning edge for Black. }
18... Bd7 19. Bf4
{ Or  19.Qxe8  Rxe8  20.Rxe8  Bxe8  21.Bxd5  Qe5  22.Be4  c4  23.Be3  cxd3  24.Bxd3  Bc6  , and Black has a winning advantage. }
19... Rxe5 20. Bxe5 Qc8 21. Bxd5 Bc6
{ And again, there is a lot of work to do, but the engines think Black is winning. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "b pawn systems"]
[Black "1 b3.  The trendy new main line. (1)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Despite it's meek looking appearance, b3 is a serious move - especially in blitz and bullet.  White can play it either before, or after Nf3.  Playing Nf3 first blocks the f pawn, but rules out 1....e5.  Playing 1 b3 allows Black to challenge for the centre immediately, and I think we should do so. }
1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3
{ Now for years the big line was 3...d5.  White attacks the centre as hard as he can - Bb5, f4 etc; Black counters with Bd6, Q - h4- e7.  White can often win a pawn but end up in trouble as a result.  If played properly though I suspect the positions end up favouring White, and they are certainly tricky if you aren't used to them.  The same could be said for the lines I do recommend I suppose, but the engines like them.  And they have gradually been played more and more - one could call them the new main line.  I propose two subsystems. }
3... Nf6 4. Bb5 Bd6
{ The key move.  Black plans OO, Re8, bishop somewhere and ...d5.   Bxc6 is met by dc, letting the light square bishop out.  This can be very comfortable for Black, so the main line is }
5. Na3
{ preparing Nc4.  Now I suggest two systems.  I think 5...e4 is a very good move, but first we will look at the main line, which is also good and particularly amusing. }
5... Na5
{ Black takes control of c4; if the White knight lands there now it will be taken. }
6. Be2
{ White's bishop now looks misplaced, so he retreats it and threatens Nb5 instead. }
6... a6 { So we stop that. } 7. c4 { White's main try is to grab some space }
7... O-O 8. Nc2
{ ... and he has various option here too.  This one is currently by far the most common. }
8... Re8 9. d3 b5
{ Black mostly plays Bf8 here with the idea of soon following with d6 or d5.  But the engines like b5, so lets have  look. }
10. Nf3 c5 11. O-O Bb7 12. e4
{ White clamps d5 and turns the Nc2 into a proper piece. } 12... Bc7
{ An odd square, but we have to keep e5 protected. } 13. Ne3 Nc6 14. Nd5 d6
{ As the cliche goes... "with chances for both sides". } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "b pawn systems"]
[Black "1 b3.  The trendy new main line. (2)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Despite it's meek looking appearance, b3 is a serious move - especially in blitz and bullet.  White can play it either before, or after Nf3.  Playing Nf3 first blocks the f pawn, but rules out 1....e5.  Playing 1 b3 allows Black to challenge for the centre immediately, and I think we should do so. }
1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3
{ Now for years the big line was 3...d5.  White attacks the centre as hard as he can - Bb5, f4 etc; Black counters with Bd6, Q - h4- e7.  White can often win a pawn but end up in trouble as a result.  If played properly though I suspect the positions end up favouring White, and they are certainly tricky if you aren't used to them.  The same could be said for the lines I do recommend I suppose, but the engines like them.  And they have gradually been played more and more - one could call them the new main line.  I propose two subsystems. }
3... Nf6 4. Bb5 Bd6
{ The key move.  Black plans OO, Re8, bishop somewhere and ...d5.   Bxc6 is met by dc, letting the light square bishop out.  This can be very comfortable for Black, so the main line is }
5. Na3 e4
{ My second suggestion.  In the main line this seems to lead to a sort of weird reverse Winawer.  Choose whichever line appeals to you more, or learn both to make things harder for the 1 b3 regulars : }
6. Nc4 Be7 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. Ne2 O-O 9. O-O a5
{ This position is rare bit has been played by some very high level players - Jobava and Rapport with White, Bacrot, Karjakin and Yu with Black. }
10. Ng3 d5 11. Ne5 Qe8 { Don't forget to defend your c pawn! } 12. c4
{ High level games thus far have gone Bd6 or Ba6.   The following is engine analysis. }
12... a4 13. d4 { f4 could be played immediately; we would take en passant. }
13... h6
{ Black prepares the move f6 to kick the knight on e5 and safeguard the f file. }
14. f4 exf3 15. Qxf3 Nh7
{ The position is rich and unexplored and the engines like Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "b pawn systems"]
[Black "The Sokolsky"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is known as the Sokolsky, or Orang Utan.  I will go with the former.  Because I like Orang Utans. }
1. b4
{ 1 b4 can be the introduction to a proper system.  In practice, it rarely is, especially in blitz.  You get all kinds of nonsense after this move.  Still, it is good to see the main line, where White at least tries to follow up sensibly. }
1... e5 { Again, ...e5 is the critical reply. } 2. Bb2 Bxb4
{ Best, despite swapping a wing for a centre pawn.  In return Black gets a lead in development, and, a least for a while, more of the centre.  Black outscores White from here. }
3. Bxe5 Nf6
{ With the Be5 a tempting target, it is easy to forget this move.  And best if you don't. }
4. Nf3 O-O 5. e3 d5 6. Be2
{ 'Theory' mostly concentrates on c4. Black plays the same way as our main line, meeting ...d5 cd with Nxd5 and perhaps playing Bf5 instead of g4.  In general, he scores even more heavily. }
6... c5 7. O-O Nc6 { Finally, we gain our tempo. } 8. Bb2 Re8 9. d3 h6 10. c3
Ba5 11. Nbd2 Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 13. Rb1 Qe7
{ Black is better, rather than merely comfortable.  Bc7 , Qd6 and Rad8 will probably follow soon. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "You know the only thing that comes out of Birds.."]
[Black "The Stonewall"]
[Result "*"]

{ Ah, the Stonewall.  Played with Black, against 1 d4, a perfectly reasonable defence.  With White, it's not bad either, as long as Black replies ...d5.  Let's not.  Although this is clearly an f4 system, White players typically enter it via 1 d4, 2 e3, 3 Bd3, so that is the move order I will give here. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 g6 3. Bd3 Bg7 4. f4 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6. O-O c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Nbd2
e5
{ White scores a magnificent 19% from here on Chess Assistant's main database, and around 23% on lichess.  This is probably the opening you should most look forward to playing against.  Black's ideas include taking multiple times on d4  (and, if a pawn survives there, on c3)  , and once the centre opens up a bit, Qb6 and Ng4.  White is already worse with best play.  But that's hardly relevant because he very rarely finds best play to begin with. }
9. fxe5
{ This mistake is most common in practice.  And it usually gets better... }
9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Qxd3 { Ng4 is good; this is better. } 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Nb3
Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Be7
{ Black is a bishop pair, a pawn structure and a development up. } *

