{ Ah, the Stonewall.  Played with Black, against 1 d4, a perfectly reasonable defence.  With White, it's not bad either, as long as Black replies ...d5.  Let's not.  Although this is clearly an f4 system, White players typically enter it via 1 d4, 2 e3, 3 Bd3, so that is the move order I will give here. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 g6 3. Bd3 Bg7 4. f4 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6. O-O c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Nbd2
e5
{ White scores a magnificent 19% from here on Chess Assistant's main database, and around 23% on lichess.  This is probably the opening you should most look forward to playing against.  Black's ideas include taking multiple times on d4  (and, if a pawn survives there, on c3)  , and once the centre opens up a bit, Qb6 and Ng4.  White is already worse with best play.  But that's hardly relevant because he very rarely finds best play to begin with. }
9. fxe5
{ This mistake is most common in practice.  And it usually gets better... }
9... dxe5 10. Nxe5 { Slightly less terrible, but still bad. } 10... Nxe5 11.
dxe5 Ng4 12. Nf3 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5
{ Now Black is just a development and a pawn structure up.  But fear not, White's most common next move on lichess is... }
