[Black "The Stonewall (3)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Ah, the Stonewall.  Played with Black, against 1 d4, a perfectly reasonable defence.  With White, it's not bad either, as long as Black replies ...d5.  Let's not.  Although this is clearly an f4 system, White players typically enter it via 1 d4, 2 e3, 3 Bd3, so that is the move order I will give here. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 g6 3. Bd3 Bg7 4. f4 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6. O-O c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Nbd2
e5 9. fxe5 dxe5 10. Bb5 cxd4 11. exd4
{ They should play cd,  but nobody ever does... } 11... exd4 12. Bxc6 dxc3 13.
Ba4 { Bxb7 Bxb7 just makes things worse  (-3 in computer speak) } 13... Qb6+
14. Kh1 cxd2 15. Bxd2 Ne4
{ We are currently a pawn up; and the computer evaluation is 2 pawns up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "You know the only thing that comes out of Birds.."]
[Black "The Stonewall:  White's miserable best."]
[Result "*"]

{ Ah, the Stonewall.  Played with Black, against 1 d4, a perfectly reasonable defence.  With White, it's not bad either, as long as Black replies ...d5.  Let's not.  Although this is clearly an f4 system, White players typically enter it via 1 d4, 2 e3, 3 Bd3, so that is the move order I will give here. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 g6 3. Bd3 Bg7 4. f4 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6. O-O c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Nbd2
e5 9. dxe5 { White should capture this way. } 9... dxe5 10. Ne4
{ And follow up with this. This leaves him almost equal - and with some attacking chances if we go wrong. }
10... exf4
{ Houdini likes the immediate Re8.  Stockfish plays ef first.  Both seem fine.  We will go with Stockfish, even though starting to liberate the bishop on c1 looks a little odd.  Re8, abandoning f7 also looks a little strange, but everything is under control... }
11. exf4 Re8 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bc4 Bg4
{ Be6 and Bf5  (meeting Ng5 with Re7)  also have a lot going for them.  But lets allow our opponent to play a little combination. }
14. Bxf7+
{ Qb3? is refuted by the pawn sacrifice Na5 Bxf7+ Kg7 and suddenly White is in a real mess. }
14... Kxf7 15. Ng5+ Bxg5 16. fxg5+ { Qxg4?? Bf6 wins a piece for Black. } 16...
Bf5 17. Qxd8 Raxd8 18. g4 Rd5 19. gxf5 Rxf5
{ In this ending Black has a lead in development, his king is a little more centeralised and White's bishop is slightly bad.  All this adds up to a Black advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "You know the only thing that comes out of Birds.."]
[Black "Birds:  Early e4."]
[Result "*"]

{ The Bird's, proper.  For my opinion of it, see the chapter heading.  And I don't mean eggs. }
1. f4 g6 2. Nf3
{ 2...d5 rules out e4 and may even be slightly better, if you don't mind playing a less crushing system against the Stonewall. }
2... Bg7 3. e4 d5 4. e5 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bg4 8. Bb5
{ White will often put this bishop on e2 but it is misplaced there.  Bd3 would be more natural if it weren't for the whole "losing the d pawn" issue.  So White may try to prepare that with Be3, but that runs into Nh6 Bd3 Qb6.  Bb5 looks a little odd but can be annoying. }
8... Rc8 { So that we don't have to play bc if White captures on c6. } 9. O-O
e6 10. Nc3 Ne7 11. h3
{ Normally, our plan would be h5, Nf5, B-f8-e7 , K-f8-g7 and Qb6.  But if White forces things we have a more direct alternative. }
11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3
{ Rxf3 improves slightly.  Though Black is still fine after 12...a6, 12....f6 or 12...OO }
12... O-O 13. Be3 f6
{ White's centre starts to come under pressure and Black is probably a little better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "You know the only thing that comes out of Birds.."]
[Black "Birds: e3 systems"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Bird's, proper.  For my opinion of it, see the chapter heading.  And I don't mean eggs. }
1. f4 g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. e3 { Playing like a reverse classical Dutch. } 3... Nf6
4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O { White would like to dominate the e5 square... } 5... d6
{ There is nothing wrong with ...d5 but taking e5 from his pieces makes sense. }
6. d3 c5 7. e4
{ White's main plan here is to swing his Queen around to h4, play f5 and then Bh6 and Ng5.  He is then read for fg, Rxf6 and Qxh7.  Our plan is a little more nebulous:  "Play on the queenside and perhaps the centre". }
7... Nc6 8. Nc3
{ The good news is that this position has very few takers with White among strong players.  And among weaker players, White seems to have a terrible score.  Black players have mostly played Bg4 here and score around 80%.  But I'm not convinced it is best, so I will give both Bg4 and Rb8 as alternatives. }
8... Rb8 9. a4 a6 10. Qe1 e6 11. f5 { This seems to be the wrong move order. }
11... exf5 12. Qh4 d5 13. exd5 Nxd5
{ White is a pawn down and his attack isn't really getting anywhere. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "You know the only thing that comes out of Birds.."]
[Black "The Stonewall with Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

{ Ah, the Stonewall.  Played with Black, against 1 d4, a perfectly reasonable defence.  With White, it's not bad either, as long as Black replies ...d5.  Let's not.  Although this is clearly an f4 system, White players typically enter it via 1 d4, 2 e3, 3 Bd3, so that is the move order I will give here. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 g6 3. f4
{ White plays a little twist:  he plans a different future for his bishop than the d3 square. }
3... Bg7 4. Nf3 O-O 5. c3 d6 6. Bc4
{ And here it is.  This may not actually be much better than the main line, but it does set some different problems.  One could argue that f7 is more tender than g6, and there are no problems with a loose bishop on d3 like in the previous examples. }
6... c5 7. O-O Qc7
{ Our standard plan from the main line is still ok, but not as effective:   7...Nc6  8.Nbd2  e5  9.fxe5  dxe5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.dxe5  Ng4  12.Nf3  Qxd1  13.Rxd1  Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Bxe5  15.e4  for example seems fine for White, and  10.dxc5  Qe7  11.b4  can also be annoying.   The computers like Qc7, and it has a number of good points: it sets up a threat to the Bc4, keeping White honest and more or less forcing Nbd2; it guards the e7 pawn; and in some lines it threatens ...d5  - it helps control the e5 square and may even be followed by cxd4 exd4 Qxf4. }
8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. Qe1
{ White has a variety of options and this probably isn't the computer's first choice; but it is thematic and by far the most commonly played. }
9... cxd4 10. exd4 Bf5
{ Highlighting a downside of Bc4; we get firm control of the f5 and e4 squares. }
11. Nh4
{ It looks natural to try to drive the bishop away.  If White does nothing Black should play on the queenside  (probably involving ...b5 - ...b4)  .  He just needs to make sure he doesnt have an accident on the e- file. }
11... e6
{ At first I rebelled against this move, but the engines are adamant.  For one thing, White may refuse to capture with the knight, and instead try to trap the bishop with h3 and g4; but this is very hard to arrange - Black can play h5 if necessary and he can often as a last resort escape to the c2 square or simply sacrifice on g4.  But what about White's other threat? }
12. Nxf5 exf5
{ Wow!  At first sight, White just gains the bishop pair and 'ruins Black's structure'.  But the engines love the Black position, and with a little thought it isn't hard to see why.  White can forget about playing f5 any time soon.  The e4 square firmly belongs to Black, but White still can't exploit the e5 square.  White's bishops are cramped  (especially the dark square one)  and Black can play something like Re8, a6, b5 Na5, Rab8 and maybe even Q-c6-d5 and attack on the queenside.  Note:  White's position will improve if he can get the move d5 in; the battle over the next few moves  (should)  revolve around a fight for the c4 and d5 squares. }
13. Bd3 a6 14. Nf3 { 14. c4 would be nice if it didn't drop the d- pawn. }
14... b5 15. Rf2 { To try to control the e- file } 15... Rfe8
{ The immediate   15...b4  is also very good. } 16. Re2 Na5
{ With a bind, and play on the queenside.  Black has further moves like Qc6  (controlling d5)  , Bh6  (inviting further weakening with g3)  , Nd5  (providing the Re8 is safe)  , Rab8  (or Rac8)  and ...b4.  White has moves too of course - but it is much harder for him to find constructive ones. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 Nf3 and move order tricks"]
[Black "Rare moves:  Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ THE GENERAL PHILOSOPHY OF PLAYING AGAINST SIDELINES.  In theory, it is easy enough to equalise against most of the 'minor' moves in a variety of ways.  In practice, there are a lot of secondary issues to consider.  First of all, your opponent will probably be more familiar with the resulting positions, giving him a practical edge, if not a theoretical one.  Having specific counters we play regularly and regard as 'our' answer to these moves largely offsets this.   Secondly, we have to consider possible transpositions into lines we don't play.  1...d5  is a good move against  Nf3  , but after  2.d4  we may get some kind of Queen's gambit. Likewise,  1...c5  is good if you are happy with a symmetrical English. But after  2.e4  we have a Sicilian - a perfectly good outcome, but only if you are an experienced Sicilian player. The lines you select have to fit in with the rest of your repertoire and preferred style of play.   One thing worth noting before we being:  1...g6  is good against almost all unorthodox moves, except perhaps 1  h4!  If you want a reliable fall back,  1...g6  ,  2...Bg7  is usually a good option.  Then there is the question of the centre.  if White neglects it we should seize it ourselves - in principle.  In practice, White can often hit back in the centre and trip us up.  After a lot of thought  I have selected the following options:   Against  1.Nf3  we play  1...g6.  I was going to go for  1...Nf6  , which is logical and by far the most popular. But there were difficult problems to solve after a lot of White options, especially  2.c4  and  2.b3  1... g6 fits in well with most of our repertoire and allows us to play some tricky sidelines against most of White's options.  It is surprisingly easy for White to end up worse after only a few moves.  These lines may not withstand a high level correspondence tournament however!   Against  1.g3  I am opting for  1...e5.  g3  can be very good if played with specific ideas, but we should be alright if our opponent transposes into a King's indian attack or closed Sicilian reversed.  We can also take the initiative quite quickly if, as so often happens White plays in a sloppy reversed Pirc fashion and just makes it up as he goes along.   Against  1.e3  - often played as a mouse slip! - we have to be a little careful. Both  1... e5 2. d4  (and)  1... d5 2. d4  (give us reasonable positions, but no the type we really want.  Instead there are two good  replies.)  1... g6  is good, but the one which suits us most is  1...Nf6  Unfortunately, we lose the option to push our f- pawn early - eg  ...f5  against White hippos, or  ...f6  against reversed Pircs - but everything else is good. It should be easy to transpose into 'our' lines if White plays an English, a  b3  system, the Birds or a stonewall. Against 'e3 poison' lines with  1.e3  Nf6  2.d4  we will play an  e3  Grunefeld if allowed, eg against  2...g6  3.c4  Bg7  4.Nc3?!  O-O  5.Nf3  d5!  with  ...c5  to come.   After  1.e3  Nf6  2.d4  g6  3.Nf3  Bg7  4.c4  O-O  5.Be2!  however, we have to be careful. A Grunefeld response is not very good here -  5...d5?  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.e4!  +/=, so instead we opt for  5.Be2  c5.  If White allows  6...cxd4  followed by  7...d5  we are happy, so the critical try is  6.d5.  These  e3  benonis score well for Black in practice but are remarkably hard to make work theoretically. I have found some lines I am more or less satisfied with.   1.d3  really should be harmless - or rather, transpositional. White can angle for an English, a King's Indian attack, a Hippo or a reversed Philidor - possibly in the form of a 'White Lion'. I like  1...e5  here, though we do need to be ready for the Lion approach, as well as  2.e4  Nc6  3.f4.  If you want something safer, try  1.d3  c5.   1.c3  is altogether sneakier. Just look at this:  1.c3  e5  2.d4  exd4  3.cxd4  d5  4.Nc3  , and we are playing the Black side of an exchange Queen's gambit. Yuck! On the plus side, White is now really committed to playing a quick  d4  (if he wants anything from the opening.)  1... b6  (and)  1...f5  (are quite good here if you like that sort of thing.)  1... d5  (leads to dull positions after)  2. d4  (and)  1... c5  can lead to exchange slav like positions if followed by  ...cxd4  too soon. Instead, we stay flexible with  1...Nf6  , intending  2...g6  and probably leading to a Torre or London.   1.Nc3  is tricky. It is worth knowing that  1...e5  (may not be very good.)  1... c5  (or)  1... c6  (are fine if you like Sicilians or Caro Kanns respectively.)  1...g6  (is only ok if you have some concrete ideas after)  2. e4  - either entering a Pirc or modern or perhaps a  g6  Sicilian. Instead this is a rare time when I like  1...d5  - we should not be scared of a Veresov, and after the main Dunst move,  2.e4  , we intend  2...dxe4  3.Nxe4  Nc6.   Finally,  1.a4  ,  1.h4  ,  1.f3  etc are also on the to - do list. Way, way, down the list, just below polishing my finger nails and learning the accordion. But who knows, they may get a brief look one. day. }
1... g6 *

