[Black "A nice line against the 1 Nf3 KIA."]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 g6 2. g3 Bg7 3. Bg2
{ White builds his castle, and probably doesn't expect play to become critical for a while.  But after }
3... e5
{ he has to make sure he doesn't drift into a worse position.  The fianchetto variation is an irritating line to play against as a Pirc player - even a tempo up! }
4. O-O
{ White's best idea is to hope for an Alekhine style position.  We could push on to e4, but it is better to consolidate the centre. }
4... d5 5. d3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Nge7 7. e4 O-O 8. exd5
{ Against  8.c3  a5  White will probably transpose soon with  9.exd5  , but  8...d4  may be worth a try if you are feeling ambitious. }
8... Nxd5 9. Re1
{ Now almost all games have continued ...Re8, but Leela finds a nice idea: }
9... a5
{ A typical neural net preference. Though Stockfish's idea of  9...Re8  10.Nc4  Nb6!  also looks good for Black. }
10. c3 { Yhe point is that  10.a4?  is well met by  Ndb4  =+ } 10... a4 11. Nc4
Re8 { And Black is already slightly better, planning ...h6 and f5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 Nf3 and move order tricks"]
[Black "A good Sniper"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 g6 2. c4 { The "English" approach. } 2... Bg7 3. Nc3
{ This is White's most common move here. But possibly not very good. Especially if he is angling for a Maroczy bind. }
3... c5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This is uncomfortable for White because he hasn't had time to play e4 and Be3. }
6. Nc2
{ 6.Nc6  bxc6  just strengthens Black's centre and gives him the b- file while losing the  d5  square.  6.Nc2  is common, aiming to get a Maroczy anyway... }
6... Bxc3+
{ A case where the doubled pawns  (and weak squares around them)  outweigh the loss of the bishop.  Black is already better, at least practically. }
7. bxc3 Nf6 { The following is a thematic sequence. } 8. f3 Qa5 9. e4
{ White keeps offering the c3 pawn.  Black can happily take it, but it is probably even better to delay. }
9... O-O 10. Ne3 b6 { Even stronger than d6. } 11. Nd5 Ba6 12. Nxf6+
{ Very tempting.  But Be2 or Bg5 was better. } 12... exf6 13. Kf2 Rac8 14. Be3
Ne5 *

