1. g4
{ Ugh.  These guys basically hope you will fall for a trap in a quagmire of unsound nonsense.  Let's see it happen to them.  Explanations in the next line. }
1... d5 2. Bg2 c6 3. h3 e5 4. d4 e4 5. c4 Bd6 6. Nc3 Ne7 7. Qb3 a5 8. Bg5 a4 9.
Nxa4 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 dxc4 11. Qxc4 Qxg5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Oh, grow up!"]
[Black "The Grob.  White insists on playing on."]
[Result "*"]

1. g4 d5 2. Bg2
{ White hopes you will take on g4.  Which is actually completely playable  . }
2... c6 3. h3
{ White really ought to guard g4 now.  If he plays 3 c4?! then dc is very good for Black. }
3... e5 4. d4 e4 5. c4 Bd6 6. Nc3 Ne7
{ In this strange "Advance French reversed" structure we develop our knight to e7, out of range of g5 hits and possibly going to g6, where it will look at the weak squares f4 and h4. }
7. Qb3 a5
{ Despite being the top choice of both Stockfish 10 and Houdini 6, nobody seems to have played this move.  Still, it is very strong.  Is Black winning yet or just nearly winning?  We will leave that to the philosophers.  Black is going to try to sacrifice this pawn with ...a4.  And with White's bishop on g5, accepting it loses a piece. }
8. Bg5
{ This is the move that White would play if Black had castled.  It isn't very good here. }
8... a4
{ In reply, we get this nudge in.  We don't actually care if it eventually drops off. }
9. Nxa4 { However, we are positively delighted if it drops off straight away! }
9... Qa5+ 10. Nc3 dxc4 11. Qxc4 Qxg5
{ Most players would resign here.  But a Grob player in a speed match?  Of course not!  So, a few more moves: }
12. Nxe4
{ First order of business:  we have won a piece but our queen and bishop are forked. }
12... Qa5+ 13. Kf1 Bc7 14. Nf3
{ Now we want to continue developing and get a knight to f6. } 14... Nd7 15.
Nfg5 { ... but of course we have to stop mate in 1... } 15... O-O 16. h4 Nd5
{ ... and we want to be able to meet Nf6 Nxf6 with NXN } 17. h5 h6
{ We don't want to allow White to play h6, and this also kicks the White knight }
18. Nf3
{ Now the other knight will probably be swapped, but we may as well gain a tempo on it before we play Nf6 }
18... Re8 19. Qc2 N7f6 { Finally! } 20. Nxf6+ Nxf6 21. g5 hxg5 22. h6 g4
{ Most Grob players I know would see this as 'With compensation'.  Most computers I know see this as '-7'.  Take your pick! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Oh, grow up!"]
[Black "The Grob.  Tales of a lesser nope."]
[Result "*"]

1. g4 d5 2. Bg2
{ White hopes you will take on g4.  Which is actually completely playable  . }
2... c6 3. h3
{ White really ought to guard g4 now.  If he plays 3 c4?! then dc is very good for Black. }
3... e5 4. d4 e4 5. c4 Bd6 6. Nc3 Ne7 7. Qb3 a5 8. Bd2
{ Let's let White play something sensible instead.  Because, why wouldn't he? }
8... a4
{ A red flag to a bull.  And why not.  He gets his mess - but it is our mess.  And it is simply good for Black.   ('bull' is the truncated version.) }
9. Nxa4
{ Compared with the last position, the White bishop is on d2 rather than g5, so this doesn't immediately lose.  Indeed, the question arises:  how do we find compensation? }
9... dxc4
{ The answer is surprising. We voluntarily collapse our own pawn centre.  And despite being behind in development!  (White's development is a mess, but he only has two pieces in between his rooks, while we have four)  .  The idea is to develop quickly with threats, in particular the idea of N-a6-b4-c2.  Although we have won back our initial sacrificed pawn  (and we will probably try to keep the c- pawn)  , to make this work we will have to sacrifice our e- and f- pawns, at least temporarily.  it should be worth it though, because if we do it right we can hack him up. }
10. Qc2 { Qxc4? b5 of course. } 10... f5 11. Nc3
{ Or 11 gf Bxf5 and if he then exchanges on e4 he loses the a4 knight. } 11...
Na6 12. gxf5 { a3?! wouldn't stop Nb4 of course. } 12... Nb4 { With tempo. }
13. Qc1 e3
{ Opening the e- file and the b1 - h7 diagonal.  Reminds me of the famous Morphy pawn sacrifice in the Falkbeer counter gambit game against Schulten. }
14. Bxe3 Bxf5
{ Only 1 pawn down, but with good "King's gambit" type play on the kingside and an "semi slav style extra pawn" on the queenside.  Nc2+ is the immediate threat. }
15. Ne4 b5 16. a3 Nbd5 17. Bd2 O-O
{ Black is winning, despite White's extra pawn.  He will probably follow up with Bxe4 and Nf5.  The difference in king safety and development is too much. }
*

